I wanted Kuechly to retire 3 years ago, but I was never going to be ready to actually see it.

Every game he played since his multiple public concussions, I held my breath. I just want him to be ok.

CTE and mental illness are as closely related as twin siblings. I wouldn't wish either on anybody.

Teach your kids baseball, basketball, and golf. Soccer is great, but they've done studies of CTE-like symptoms from years of repeated headers.

I don't care if you've got 50 trillion dollars. If your brain isn't right, you'd give it all away just to be able to think clearly.

snippet.textDisplay: You know what change I'm most happy about? NFL fans are reacting to these early retirements by overwhelmingly supporting the players (maybe not initially upon hearing the news like the Andrew Luck announcement, but after sitting on it for some time, the support is there). It used to be that players were expected to play until they were too slow or too hurt to keep going, that retiring while young and healthy meant risking being labeled something negative (unless the player was a best-of-the-best superstar like Jim Brown). Now fans understand that players must do what's best for their own health and bodies.
